{{For|a cue for music in film or theater|Cue (theatrical)}}
{{For|music played while a performer enters|Entrance music}}
[[Image:cuenotes.GIF|thumb|400px|An example of cue notes. This example from the 2nd horn part ''Overture to Der Freischütz'' contains cue notes showing the 4th and 3rd horn parts, in order to aid proper entrance. {{audio|Cuenotes.mid|Play}}]]
[[File:Cue notes.png|thumb|Cue in orchestral music]]

In [[musical notation]], a '''cue note''' is or '''cue notes''' are indications informing [[musician|players]], "of important passages being played by other instruments, [such as an] '''entrance''' after a long period of [[rest (music)|rest]]."<ref name="McGrain">McGrain, Mark (1990). ''Music Notation'', p.183. Hal Leonard. {{ISBN|9781476867052}}.</ref> A cue may also function as a guideline for another instrument for [[musical improvisation]] or if there are many bars rest to help the performer find where to come in.

"Cue notes may be given as guidance only, to assist a performer's entrance after numerous measures of rest....[Their size, and all elements associated with them] is somewhat smaller than normal note size, but still large enough to be legible (65-75% of normal note size)."<ref>Gerou, Tom & Lusk, Linda (1996). ''Essential Dictionary of Music Notation'', p.119. Alfred Music Publishing. {{ISBN|9781457410710}}.</ref>

The cued instrument is indicated with text and the cue notes are smaller than the rest. The [[stem (music)|stems]] of cue notes all go in the same direction and cue notes are [[transposing instrument|transposed]] into the key of the part entering.<ref name="McGrain"/>

== Other definitions ==

There are also passages in certain scores where there is an indication above a line of notes saying "cue notes" or simply "cue", but this indication does not have anything to do with the "cue notes" explained above. Opposed to these, these "cue notes" are more like alternative notes, which can either be played or not played, depending on the conductor's decision. This practice is particularly common in recordings of orchestral film music, where they often like to try out several orchestral colors and weightings in just one recording session and therefore use cued passages to try out other options.

